The White House press secretary, Josh Earnest, announced that President Obama has met with Vice President Biden and law enforcement leaders to discuss the recent tragedy in Dallas and the challenges that law enforcement officers face across the country. The President is also preparing to travel to Dallas to attend a memorial service for the five police officers who were killed in the shooting. On Wednesday, the President will convene a meeting at the White House that will include law enforcement officials, activists, academics, civil rights leaders, and local political leaders to discuss solutions for repairing the bonds of trust between law enforcement and the communities they serve. The President believes that implementing best practices for community policing is an important step towards improving relationships and reducing crime. The article also mentions that the President has been frustrated with the lack of progress on gun control and the need for more funding to address the Zika virus.